 and time again, people err in predicting what will make them happy, overestimating the import of money and mistaking the circumstances to which they can and cannot adapt. Drawing on new research in psychology, neuroscience, and economics, the authors of Happiness and the Law assess how the law affects people’s quality of life—and how it can do so in a better way. Taking readers through some of the common questions about and objections to the use of happiness research in law and policy, they consider two areas in depth: criminal punishment and civil lawsuits. More broadly, the book proposes a comprehensive approach to assessing human welfare—well-being analysis—that is a valuable alternative to the strictly economically based cost-benefit analyses currently dominating how we evaluate public policy. The study of happiness is the next step in the evolution from traditional economic analysis of the law to a behavioral approach. Happiness and the Law will serve as the definitive, yet accessible, guide to understanding this new paradigm.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHappiness. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 0aWell-being. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBuccafusco, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMasur, Jonathan S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226195667423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226195667.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles